    "name": "Castle Stalker",
    "country": "scotland",
    "region": "argyll-western-isles",
    "county": "Argyll and Bute",
    "lat": "56.57111111",
    "lng": "-5.38611111",
    "mapsLink": "https://www.google.com/maps/search/Castle%20Stalker%20Argyll%20and%20Bute%20scotland",
    "image": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6a/Castle_Stalker_-_geograph.org.uk_-_204092.jpg/330px-Castle_Stalker_-_geograph.org.uk_-_204092.jpg",
    "imgSource": "wikipedia",
    "gallery": [
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/castle-stalker-2.jpg",
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/castle-stalker-3.jpg",
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/castle-stalker-4.jpg",
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/castle-stalker-5.jpg",
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/castle-stalker-main-2.jpg",
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/castle-stalker-main-3.jpg",
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/castle-stalker-main-4.jpg",
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/castle-stalker-main-5.jpg"
    ],
    "desc": "Castle Stalker is a four-storey tower house or keep in the Scottish county of Argyll. It is set on a tidal islet on Loch Laich, an inlet off Loch Linnhe. It is about 1+1⁄2 miles north-east of Port Appin and is visible from the A828 road about midway between Oban and Glen Coe. The islet is accessible with difficulty from the shore at low tide. The name \"Stalker\" comes from the Gaelic Stalcaire, meaning \"hunter\" or \"falconer\". The island castle is one of the best preserved medieval tower houses to survive in western Scotland and is a Category A listed building. It stands in the Lynn of Lorn National Scenic Area.",
    "type": "tower house",
    "period": "14th century",
    "rating": 4.4,
    "tags": [
      "photogenic",
      "filming-location",
      "hidden-gem"
    ],
    "source": "",
    "wiki": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Castle_Stalker"
