  {
    "name": "Coldingham Priory",
    "country": "scotland",
    "region": "borders",
    "county": "Scottish Borders",
    "lat": "55.8865",
    "lng": "-2.15522",
    "mapsLink": "https://www.google.com/maps/search/Coldingham%20Priory%20Scottish%20Borders%20scotland",
    "image": "https://img.castlecore.uk/coldingham-priory.jpg",
    "imgSource": "CDN",
    "gallery": [
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/coldingham-priory-2.jpg",
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/coldingham-priory-3.jpg",
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/coldingham-priory-4.jpg",
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/coldingham-priory-5.jpg"
    ],
    "desc": "Coldingham Priory was a house of Benedictine monks. It lies on the south-east coast of Scotland, in the village of Coldingham, Berwickshire. Coldingham Priory was founded in the reign of David I of Scotland, although his older brother and predecessor King Edgar of Scotland had granted the land of Coldingham to the Church of Durham in 1098, and a church was constructed by him and presented in 1100. The first prior of Coldingham is on record by the year 1147, although it is likely that the foundation was much earlier. The earlier monastery at Coldingham was founded by St Æbbe sometime c. AD 640. Although the monastery was largely destroyed by Oliver Cromwell in 1650, some remains of the priory exist, the choir of which forms the present parish church of Coldingham and is serviced by the Church of Scotland.",
    "type": "abbey",
    "period": "11th century",
    "rating": 4,
    "tags": [
      "well-preserved",
      "medieval",
      "atmospheric",
      "gothic",
      "free-entry",
      "coastal"
    ],
    "source": "",
    "wiki": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coldingham_Priory",
    "wikiImage": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b4/Berwickshire%2C_COLDINGHAM%2C_Coldingham_Priory_%2835964550806%29.jpg/330px-Berwickshire%2C_COLDINGHAM%2C_Coldingham_Priory_%2835964550806%29.jpg"
  },
  {
    "name": "Craigmillar Castle",
    "country": "scotland",
    "region": "edinburgh-lothians",
    "county": "Edinburgh",
    "lat": "55.9259",
    "lng": "-3.1406",
    "mapsLink": "https://www.google.com/maps/search/Craigmillar%20Castle%20Edinburgh%20scotland",
    "image": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ae/Craigmillar_Castle.jpg/330px-Craigmillar_Castle.jpg",
    "imgSource": "wikipedia",
    "gallery": [
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/craigmillar-castle-2.jpg",
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/craigmillar-castle-3.jpg",
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/craigmillar-castle-4.jpg",
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/craigmillar-castle-5.jpg",
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/craigmillar-castle-main-2.jpg",
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/craigmillar-castle-main-3.jpg",
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/craigmillar-castle-main-4.jpg",
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/craigmillar-castle-main-5.jpg"
    ],
    "desc": "Craigmillar Castle is a ruined medieval castle in Edinburgh, Scotland. It is three miles (4.8 km) south-east of the city centre, on a low hill to the south of the modern suburb of Craigmillar. The Preston family of Craigmillar, the local feudal barons, began building the castle in the late 14th century and building works continued through the 15th and 16th centuries. In 1660, the castle was sold to Sir John Gilmour, Lord President of the Court of Session, who breathed new life into the ageing castle. The Gilmours left Craigmillar in the 18th century for a more modern residence, nearby Inch House, and the castle fell into ruin. It is now in the care of Historic Environment Scotland as a scheduled monument, and is open to the public.",
    "type": "castle",
    "period": "14th century",
    "rating": 4.4,
    "tags": [
      "dramatic-ruin",
      "hidden-gem",
      "filming-location"
    ],
    "source": "",
    "wiki": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Craigmillar_Castle"
  },
