  {
    "name": "Elcho Castle",
    "country": "scotland",
    "region": "fife-perthshire",
    "county": "Perth and Kinross",
    "lat": "56.3746",
    "lng": "-3.3545",
    "mapsLink": "https://www.google.com/maps/search/Elcho%20Castle%20Perth%20and%20Kinross%20scotland",
    "image": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/50/Elcho_castle.jpg/330px-Elcho_castle.jpg",
    "imgSource": "wikipedia",
    "gallery": [
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/elcho-castle-2.jpg",
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/elcho-castle-3.jpg",
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/elcho-castle-4.jpg",
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/elcho-castle-5.jpg"
    ],
    "desc": "Elcho Castle is located close to the south bank of the River Tay approximately four miles south-east of Perth, Scotland, in the region of Perth and Kinross. It was maintained by Clan Wemyss from its construction around 1560 until it was put into the care of the Secretary of State for Scotland in the early 20th century, though was not occupied for the entire time. In around 1830 it was re-roofed and a nearby cottage constructed. The castle has been a scheduled monument since 1920 on the grounds of being \"a particularly fine example of a Medieval tower-house\", and the cottage became a listed building in 1971 in recognition of its national importance. The castle is unusual in that it has both en suite guest accommodation like a mansion, but also a large number of gun loops.",
    "type": "tower house",
    "period": "16th century",
    "rating": 4.1,
    "tags": [
      "well-preserved",
      "hidden-gem"
    ],
    "source": "",
    "wiki": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elcho_Castle"
  },
  {
    "name": "Loch Leven Castle",
    "country": "scotland",
    "region": "fife-perthshire",
    "county": "Perth and Kinross",
    "lat": "",
    "lng": "",
    "mapsLink": "https://www.google.com/maps/search/Loch%20Leven%20Castle%20Perth%20and%20Kinross%20scotland",
    "image": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/df/Lochleven_west_wall.JPG/330px-Lochleven_west_wall.JPG",
    "imgSource": "wikipedia",
    "gallery": [
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/loch-leven-castle-2.jpg",
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/loch-leven-castle-3.jpg",
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/loch-leven-castle-4.jpg",
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/loch-leven-castle-5.jpg",
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/loch-leven-castle-main-2.jpg",
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/loch-leven-castle-main-3.jpg",
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/loch-leven-castle-main-4.jpg",
      "https://img.castlecore.uk/loch-leven-castle-main-5.jpg"
    ],
    "desc": "Lochleven Castle is a ruined castle on an island in Loch Leven, in the Perth and Kinross local authority area of Scotland. Possibly built around 1300, the castle was the site of military action during the Wars of Scottish Independence (1296–1357). In the latter part of the 14th century, the castle was granted to William Douglas, 1st Earl of Douglas, by his uncle. It remained in the Douglases' hands for the next 300 years. Mary, Queen of Scots, was imprisoned there in 1567–68, and forced to abdicate as queen, before escaping with the help of her gaoler's family. In 1588, the queen's gaoler inherited the title of Earl of Morton, and moved away from the castle. In 1675, Sir William Bruce, an architect, bought the castle and used it as a focal point for his garden; it was never again used as a residence.",
    "type": "castle",
    "period": "14th century",
    "rating": 4.3,
    "tags": [
      "dramatic-ruin",
      "photogenic",
      "hidden-gem"
    ],
    "source": "",
    "wiki": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lochleven_Castle"
  },
